1
00:02:18,650 --> 00:02:21,016
No, it's not a sense of betrayal, sir.

2
00:02:21,887 --> 00:02:23,354
l don't feel that.

3
00:02:24,656 --> 00:02:28,319
But l was told l would have command
of our next blockade-runner.

4
00:02:30,362 --> 00:02:33,024
l've seen myself on the bridge,
taking this ship...

5
00:02:34,599 --> 00:02:37,864
from Japan into Bordeaux.

6
00:02:37,936 --> 00:02:39,767
Do you know where l see myself?

7
00:02:40,539 --> 00:02:43,906
ln Bremen, at home in bed with my wife.

8
00:02:45,243 --> 00:02:48,406
-You have a wife, Kruse?
-No, sir.

9
00:02:49,915 --> 00:02:52,713
Well, perhaps here in Tokyo
it's just as well.

10
00:02:54,252 --> 00:02:56,447
Mr. Kruse, this cargo....

11
00:02:57,556 --> 00:02:59,956
God Almighty, how we need this cargo.

12
00:03:01,293 --> 00:03:04,023
And Capt. Mueller
is a man of such experience.

13
00:03:04,629 --> 00:03:05,857
Look here.

14
00:03:06,431 --> 00:03:11,300
Tomorrow my experience puts me here,
on a fine new Japanese submarine.

15
00:03:12,270 --> 00:03:14,864
l am to show our friends
the wolf-pack tactics we use...

16
00:03:14,940 --> 00:03:17,807
to erase so much
Allied shipping in the Atlantic.

17
00:03:18,276 --> 00:03:20,437
An assignment l do not cherish, you see.

18
00:03:20,545 --> 00:03:23,309
l'm grateful for the way
you put it, Adm. Wendel.

19
00:03:23,415 --> 00:03:27,715
The way l put it is that,
First Officer or Admiral, we do as ordered.

20
00:03:29,955 --> 00:03:33,891
lncidentally, if everything goes
according to plan...

21
00:03:34,760 --> 00:03:36,284
our paths may cross.

22
00:03:39,898 --> 00:03:43,766
Sir, Capt. Mueller's here to see you.
And he's impatient.

23
00:03:44,336 --> 00:03:47,430
lt's a bad morning. Nobody's satisfied.

24
00:03:47,606 --> 00:03:49,574
Ask Capt. Mueller to come in.

25
00:03:49,641 --> 00:03:53,839
Adm. Wendel, in the Merchant Navy,
the captain chooses his own crew.

26
00:03:54,079 --> 00:03:55,774
What are you doing here?

27
00:03:55,914 --> 00:03:59,281
l'll be damned if l'll ship with these.
Two murderers.

28
00:03:59,751 --> 00:04:01,844
Two more, ''assault with deadly weapons.''

29
00:04:01,953 --> 00:04:05,116
This one, ''theft of government property.''

30
00:04:05,190 --> 00:04:07,420
Another, an outright political enemy.

31
00:04:07,926 --> 00:04:09,985
lt's also a good way
to return these bastards...

32
00:04:10,095 --> 00:04:12,029
to Germany for the punishment
they deserve.

33
00:04:12,130 --> 00:04:14,121
l'm sorry, l cannot accept them.

34
00:04:14,199 --> 00:04:15,757
But they're only a handful, Captain--

35
00:04:15,834 --> 00:04:18,769
l don't want a handful of maggots
in my soup!

36
00:04:19,104 --> 00:04:22,198
Now, we've given you
every reliable man we could find.

37
00:04:22,440 --> 00:04:26,467
And must l remind you, Capt. Mueller,
that you can't afford to protest?

38
00:04:30,282 --> 00:04:32,842
Mr. Kruse, would you leave
the two of us alone?

39
00:04:32,951 --> 00:04:34,851
Stand right there, Mr. Kruse.

40
00:04:35,821 --> 00:04:38,654
Adm. Wendel is about
to say that my last ship...

41
00:04:38,723 --> 00:04:40,623
was torpedoed in the lndian Ocean.

42
00:04:40,692 --> 00:04:43,559
-Well, that's common knowledge--
-But at the time of the attack...

43
00:04:43,662 --> 00:04:45,152
l had a skinful of rum.

44
00:04:47,032 --> 00:04:50,001
Capt. Mueller reports that he stood on
the bridge for three days...

45
00:04:50,068 --> 00:04:51,535
with a festering jaw.

46
00:04:52,470 --> 00:04:55,906
lt was lanced.
Drugs were administered. No avail.

47
00:04:56,141 --> 00:04:58,473
Therefore, Capt. Mueller tried liquor.

48
00:04:58,577 --> 00:05:00,841
lt is said to have afforded him some relief.

49
00:05:00,912 --> 00:05:03,176
The torpedo didn't know
l had been drinking.

50
00:05:03,248 --> 00:05:05,148
We cannot interview that torpedo!

51
00:05:05,217 --> 00:05:08,516
Be satisfied that the Admiralty
retains confidence in you.

52
00:05:14,059 --> 00:05:18,018
Believe me, Mueller, take the ship.
You'll save yourself a lot of consequences.

53
00:05:18,096 --> 00:05:21,190
l can take any of your consequences.

54
00:05:22,567 --> 00:05:24,398
l wasn't referring to you.

55
00:05:25,370 --> 00:05:27,565
But you see at home,
they are inclined to believe...

56
00:05:27,672 --> 00:05:30,368
that certain behavior runs in the family.

57
00:05:34,880 --> 00:05:36,074
My son?

58
00:05:36,581 --> 00:05:39,243
He's on duty in the North Sea area,
isn't he?

59
00:05:40,452 --> 00:05:45,014
My son is a splendid officer.
One of the finest.

60
00:05:45,957 --> 00:05:48,551
-They wouldn't.
-Yes, Mueller, they would.

61
00:05:49,861 --> 00:05:51,021
They have.

62
00:06:04,109 --> 00:06:07,977
The cargo, Mr. Crain,
is perhaps the single most important...

63
00:06:08,079 --> 00:06:10,479
item in the world today.

64
00:06:11,049 --> 00:06:14,143
-Col. Statter, would you like some tea?
-No, thank you.

65
00:06:14,252 --> 00:06:17,710
-The cargo, Mr. Crain, is rubber.
-Rubber?

66
00:06:18,256 --> 00:06:20,486
A ship called the Ingo will leave Tokyo...

67
00:06:20,592 --> 00:06:23,959
carrying 7,000 tons of raw rubber.

68
00:06:24,729 --> 00:06:27,721
7,000 tons of rubber, Mr. Crain...

69
00:06:28,400 --> 00:06:32,769
will keep the entire
German army on wheels...

70
00:06:33,004 --> 00:06:35,097
for at least three months.

71
00:06:38,510 --> 00:06:41,911
-ls this music disturbing you?
-No.

72
00:06:41,980 --> 00:06:43,971
Would you like
to hear the second movement?

73
00:06:44,082 --> 00:06:45,310
No.

74
00:06:49,821 --> 00:06:52,085
l'm glad you admire my painting.

75
00:06:52,657 --> 00:06:55,421
l bought this Kirschner in Zurich.

76
00:06:55,927 --> 00:06:58,657
Yeah, l paid too much for it,
but l couldn't resist it.

77
00:06:58,763 --> 00:07:01,163
You come from Zurich, Mr. Crain?

78
00:07:02,200 --> 00:07:04,361
Yes, my family lives there.

79
00:07:05,837 --> 00:07:07,134
Mr. Crain...

80
00:07:08,340 --> 00:07:10,035
you have no family.

81
00:07:10,508 --> 00:07:12,772
You're a German, Herr Schroeder.

82
00:07:14,112 --> 00:07:16,876
You've been living
in a British dominion here in lndia...

83
00:07:16,982 --> 00:07:20,145
on a forged Swiss passport
for the last three years.

84
00:07:22,687 --> 00:07:26,282
You were a reserve officer
in an engineer demolition battalion.

85
00:07:26,524 --> 00:07:28,549
The day you received orders
to report for duty...

86
00:07:28,660 --> 00:07:30,389
you turned your back on your country...

87
00:07:30,562 --> 00:07:35,022
and managed to leave Germany
with most of your funds.

88
00:07:38,536 --> 00:07:42,199
l'm not surprised, sir, that you found me.

89
00:07:43,408 --> 00:07:46,900
-l'm only surprised that it took so long.
-Oh, but it didn't.

90
00:07:48,079 --> 00:07:51,242
We've not had any need for you, until now.

91
00:07:52,183 --> 00:07:56,381
What we're astonished at is that
you never gave your services to the Allies.

92
00:07:56,488 --> 00:07:59,753
-But buried yourself out here.
-Buried myself?

93
00:08:01,559 --> 00:08:04,551
l think l have here
all that l could possibly want.

94
00:08:05,063 --> 00:08:09,557
l have my books and my music
and a modest art collection.

95
00:08:10,535 --> 00:08:13,595
And a visit from a beautiful lady
from time to time.

96
00:08:14,706 --> 00:08:17,436
And what l value most is my privacy.

97
00:08:18,576 --> 00:08:21,340
Now let me save you some valuable time.

98
00:08:22,847 --> 00:08:26,908
Col. Statter, l have no intention
of blowing up the ship.

99
00:08:27,085 --> 00:08:31,613
We don't want you to blow up that ship.
lt's precisely what we don't want.

100
00:08:32,390 --> 00:08:34,517
We want you to save that ship.

101
00:08:36,628 --> 00:08:39,062
-To save it?
-Herr Schroeder...

102
00:08:39,197 --> 00:08:42,360
as you know,
the Allies are desperately short of rubber.

103
00:08:42,967 --> 00:08:45,527
As much as the Germans
want their cargo...

104
00:08:45,637 --> 00:08:48,128
we want it more,
and we mean to capture it.

105
00:08:48,306 --> 00:08:50,866
Yes. Well, why do you come to me?

106
00:08:52,143 --> 00:08:56,773
German blockade-runners have orders
to scuttle at the approach of an enemy.

107
00:08:57,382 --> 00:09:00,579
But if an engineer, a demolitions expert,
boards that ship...

108
00:09:00,652 --> 00:09:03,246
and disarms all the scuttling charges...

109
00:09:04,055 --> 00:09:08,890
when the captain goes to scuttle,
he's gonna be a very surprised captain.

110
00:09:09,727 --> 00:09:14,130
And also surprised will be the engineer,
if he lives to a ripe, old age.

111
00:09:14,966 --> 00:09:19,426
Obviously, there are ways in which
this adventure might not succeed.

112
00:09:20,004 --> 00:09:21,801
Yeah, perhaps a 1,000, huh?

113
00:09:21,940 --> 00:09:26,001
But if it does, the Allied governments
are gonna be very grateful indeed.

114
00:09:26,811 --> 00:09:28,210
And if it fails?

115
00:09:29,981 --> 00:09:31,881
The Germans would shoot him.

116
00:09:32,617 --> 00:09:35,142
We would've preferred a professional,
of course.

117
00:09:35,220 --> 00:09:39,452
But there wasn't a qualified man anywhere
near Tokyo to get him there in time.

118
00:09:39,524 --> 00:09:40,684
Schroeder...

119
00:09:40,992 --> 00:09:43,722
if we capture 7,000 tons of rubber...

120
00:09:44,028 --> 00:09:47,987
it's gonna save thousands of lives
and shorten the war against Hitler.

121
00:09:48,166 --> 00:09:49,394
Col. Statter...

122
00:09:50,235 --> 00:09:54,501
besides from the obvious suicidal aspects
of your scheme...

123
00:09:55,507 --> 00:10:00,069
l personally don't believe that war is ever
a solution to political conflict.

124
00:10:00,345 --> 00:10:02,142
What do wars ever prove?

125
00:10:02,714 --> 00:10:04,978
Men, women, and children
are slaughtered...

126
00:10:05,049 --> 00:10:06,983
and a generation later...

127
00:10:07,152 --> 00:10:09,552
friends are enemies,
and enemies are friends...

128
00:10:09,654 --> 00:10:12,987
and the whole stupid cycle
starts over again.

129
00:10:14,325 --> 00:10:18,386
Certainly, l have great appreciation
for your noble effort...

130
00:10:18,496 --> 00:10:21,932
and your interest
to save thousands of lives.

131
00:10:22,667 --> 00:10:27,036
But excuse me if l seem
to be concerned for my own life.

132
00:10:27,238 --> 00:10:31,231
lt's unfortunate you're rated so highly
by the Gestapo, Herr Schroeder.

133
00:10:31,543 --> 00:10:33,909
Because l'm told their penalties
for deserters...

134
00:10:34,012 --> 00:10:36,412
are somewhat more theatrical than ours.

135
00:10:37,015 --> 00:10:41,952
No, they hold you under house arrest
until after the war is over and then...

136
00:10:42,453 --> 00:10:45,581
they give you a fair trial,
as they do in England, l'm sure.

137
00:10:45,690 --> 00:10:47,715
You realize you're my prisoner?

138
00:10:48,026 --> 00:10:50,256
l can have you transported
back to England...

139
00:10:50,361 --> 00:10:53,455
and parachute you out
of an RAF plane over Germany.

140
00:10:53,865 --> 00:10:56,766
At the same time,
a valuable English officer...

141
00:10:57,535 --> 00:11:00,436
held by the Germans,
will be dropped over England.

142
00:11:02,307 --> 00:11:05,401
Exchange of hostages
is as old as war itself.

143
00:11:06,978 --> 00:11:10,470
Perhaps blackmail is a little older, huh?

144
00:11:11,783 --> 00:11:16,550
l thought the Holy British Empire
indulged in more modern ethics.

145
00:11:18,256 --> 00:11:22,124
Some arrangements are being made
for you to board that ship in Tokyo.

146
00:11:22,260 --> 00:11:25,923
But even if l am put aboard that ship,
it still might reach Germany.

147
00:11:25,997 --> 00:11:27,259
That's right.

148
00:11:27,498 --> 00:11:29,898
Or you may not be able to disarm
all the charges...

149
00:11:29,968 --> 00:11:31,458
and the ship might be scuttled.

150
00:11:32,303 --> 00:11:34,635
ln which case, you're likely to drown.

151
00:11:34,839 --> 00:11:38,605
Or be rescued by the Germans
or by the Allies.

152
00:11:38,977 --> 00:11:42,105
ln that event,
we'll still be able to make use of you.

153
00:11:43,281 --> 00:11:47,274
Col. Statter, you are morally degenerate.

154
00:11:48,253 --> 00:11:51,848
ln your case, l can't say
that l'm bothered by any moral nausea.

155
00:11:52,590 --> 00:11:56,356
No, l'm afraid the success
of the mission is your only hope.

156
00:12:08,706 --> 00:12:11,607
Couldn't you have found
a more obvious place in Calcutta?

157
00:12:11,676 --> 00:12:15,134
-Like a public comfort station?
-What did you expect?

158
00:12:15,213 --> 00:12:17,306
l'd hoped for something
a little more subtle.

159
00:12:17,382 --> 00:12:19,680
Perhaps you'd prefer
one of our local brothels.

160
00:12:19,784 --> 00:12:24,380
lt would've at least given me
some compensation for the inconvenience.

161
00:12:24,489 --> 00:12:26,719
On the return trip, my dear fellow.

162
00:12:26,824 --> 00:12:28,052
lf you return.

163
00:12:28,159 --> 00:12:32,653
-Statter, you're a cold bastard.
-l was born on a chilly island.

164
00:12:44,976 --> 00:12:47,809
Here are your personal effects:

165
00:12:49,147 --> 00:12:51,638
a picture of your wife and family...

166
00:12:54,052 --> 00:12:55,576
some German money...

167
00:12:57,689 --> 00:12:59,088
a wedding ring...

168
00:13:01,426 --> 00:13:04,554
book matches from your favorite bar
in Berlin...

169
00:13:05,029 --> 00:13:08,328
more background, further instructions,
bits and pieces...

170
00:13:08,666 --> 00:13:10,224
your dachshund.

171
00:13:11,936 --> 00:13:16,566
Don't you have some sauerkraut
and knackwurst in there for me?

172
00:13:18,443 --> 00:13:19,910
Your insignia.

173
00:13:20,745 --> 00:13:22,770
Display it at all times.

174
00:13:23,214 --> 00:13:24,909
You are a standard leader.

175
00:13:26,284 --> 00:13:28,946
A top rank member of the SS.

176
00:13:31,889 --> 00:13:35,689
You're arrogant, rude, brutal, conceited...

177
00:13:35,893 --> 00:13:38,020
which should not be difficult for you.

178
00:13:38,096 --> 00:13:40,621
Perhaps you would like to hear me sing
the Horst WesseI song?

179
00:13:40,732 --> 00:13:42,529
No, that won't be necessary.

180
00:13:43,634 --> 00:13:46,899
This is a chart
used by German merchant ships...

181
00:13:46,971 --> 00:13:50,236
the first 3,000 miles outside Tokyo.

182
00:13:50,308 --> 00:13:52,799
We've learned the course of yours.

183
00:13:52,910 --> 00:13:54,775
lf you place this pin...

184
00:13:55,079 --> 00:13:59,243
at latitude 14 degrees North,
longitude 175 East...

185
00:14:00,218 --> 00:14:02,948
as you see, it makes a circle.

186
00:14:04,088 --> 00:14:07,990
Now, depending on winds and currents,
your ship will enter this area...

187
00:14:08,092 --> 00:14:10,754
12 to 14 days out of Japan.

188
00:14:12,163 --> 00:14:15,291
And within it, waiting for you...

189
00:14:16,267 --> 00:14:18,929
will be units of the American Navy.

190
00:14:22,907 --> 00:14:27,776
-What if my ship is delayed?
-Now that's a fair question.

191
00:14:28,746 --> 00:14:31,806
Our friends will be able to wait
until the sixteenth day.

192
00:14:31,983 --> 00:14:35,146
So you see,
you have a full 48 hours leeway.

193
00:14:36,988 --> 00:14:38,012
How nice.

194
00:14:39,690 --> 00:14:43,592
The code name for that area is
the ''Keil Circle.''

195
00:14:43,661 --> 00:14:47,597
And for this operation,
you will be known as Keil.

196
00:14:48,666 --> 00:14:50,156
Keil.

197
00:14:56,007 --> 00:15:00,444
How many scuttling charges are there
on the ship, and where are they located?

198
00:15:00,711 --> 00:15:03,771
That's your riddle.
We can't be expected to know everything.

199
00:15:15,560 --> 00:15:18,825
The crew believes this
to be a routine passage...

200
00:15:18,896 --> 00:15:20,796
down the China Sea.

201
00:15:21,232 --> 00:15:24,531
Yes, for a while, sir,
only the captain, you, and l...

202
00:15:24,635 --> 00:15:26,830
are to be aware of our destination.

203
00:15:27,205 --> 00:15:29,469
There are some of the reasons.

204
00:15:38,082 --> 00:15:41,677
-You're whistling, sailor.
-Yes, sir, l like to whistle.

205
00:15:44,388 --> 00:15:46,879
There's a superstition
about whistling on a ship.

206
00:15:46,991 --> 00:15:49,585
-Beat it.
-l'm not on a ship yet.

207
00:15:51,562 --> 00:15:53,530
Stay in character, Mr. Keil.

208
00:16:00,505 --> 00:16:01,767
l am sorry but--

209
00:16:01,873 --> 00:16:06,173
-Yeah. Best to enlighten them at the start.
-Correct, Standard Leader.

210
00:16:06,277 --> 00:16:08,336
Good-bye and good luck.

211
00:16:08,779 --> 00:16:10,076
HeiI Hitler.

212
00:16:13,751 --> 00:16:15,241
Mr. Keil...

213
00:16:17,855 --> 00:16:19,015
good luck.

214
00:16:27,565 --> 00:16:31,433
Hold your fire.
We'll jump ship in Hong Kong.

215
00:16:37,308 --> 00:16:38,536
Dr. Ambach...

216
00:16:38,776 --> 00:16:41,540
-injured man coming aboard.
-Yes, sir.

217
00:16:43,714 --> 00:16:46,114
-Now, when do you leave us?
-At point seven.

218
00:16:46,217 --> 00:16:48,117
-Mr. Milkereit.
-Sir?

219
00:16:48,219 --> 00:16:51,814
-After point seven, plot course 76.
-76, yes, sir.

220
00:16:51,923 --> 00:16:52,947
All right.

221
00:16:55,960 --> 00:16:57,291
Captain...

222
00:16:57,662 --> 00:17:00,256
l have the honor
to present Mr. Hans Keil...

223
00:17:00,331 --> 00:17:03,994
of the Reich Security Agency,
Division 4E5, Far East Zone.

224
00:17:04,168 --> 00:17:07,160
Oh, yes. l was told a few hours ago
there'd be such a passenger.

225
00:17:07,271 --> 00:17:09,933
-You've assigned Mr. Keil a cabin?
-Yes, sir.

226
00:17:10,308 --> 00:17:12,606
Hope you'll be comfortable.
Check with Dr. Ambach...

227
00:17:12,677 --> 00:17:15,145
and let me know when that man is ready
to report for duty.

228
00:17:15,246 --> 00:17:18,443
-He wasn't that badly hurt, sir.
-Just take care of it.

229
00:17:22,820 --> 00:17:24,082
Capt. Mueller...

230
00:17:24,155 --> 00:17:26,749
l was wondering if you had
a few moments, if perhaps l could--

231
00:17:26,824 --> 00:17:31,022
After we clear the harbor, there'll be
plenty of time to get acquainted, Mr. Keil.

232
00:17:31,195 --> 00:17:34,961
-Good. l was looking forward to it.
-Well, l'm not.

233
00:17:35,866 --> 00:17:38,596
After all, l know your purpose
aboard my ship.

234
00:17:44,008 --> 00:17:45,270
Mr. Branner...

235
00:17:45,476 --> 00:17:47,307
starboard engine, half speed.

236
00:17:47,378 --> 00:17:49,505
Starboard! Half speed!

237
00:18:28,486 --> 00:18:33,355
lt's my belief that political soldiers are
the lifeblood of a nation.

238
00:18:33,758 --> 00:18:35,692
Even more than the military.

239
00:18:36,661 --> 00:18:38,595
Wonderful observation.

240
00:18:39,096 --> 00:18:41,030
You are a member of the party, Mr. Kruse?

241
00:18:41,098 --> 00:18:42,429
Of course, l am.

242
00:18:45,102 --> 00:18:48,765
Well, Captain,
l hope that everything is in order now.

243
00:18:49,507 --> 00:18:51,168
-lt is.
-Good.

244
00:18:51,509 --> 00:18:54,103
l see you're starting
your assignment early.

245
00:18:55,713 --> 00:18:59,774
You're wasting your time. l don't plan
to have an infected jaw this trip.

246
00:19:00,885 --> 00:19:05,515
Frankly, l'm quite surprised. l thought your
department had better use for its men.

247
00:19:07,058 --> 00:19:10,425
You don't have to be discreet.
Mr. Kruse knows all about it.

248
00:19:11,762 --> 00:19:13,059
About what?

249
00:19:15,066 --> 00:19:19,127
Well, l can see why the Security Office
felt it wise to take precautions.

250
00:19:19,737 --> 00:19:21,796
Though, l'm certain
that the captain's drinking...

251
00:19:21,906 --> 00:19:24,739
and the loss of his last ship
had no connection.

252
00:19:25,710 --> 00:19:27,405
l don't know about this...

253
00:19:27,478 --> 00:19:30,572
but l assure you this is not the reason
why l'm on the ship.

254
00:19:30,748 --> 00:19:31,806
Not at all.

255
00:19:31,916 --> 00:19:34,248
Which still means
you'll be looking over my shoulder.

256
00:19:34,318 --> 00:19:37,253
l don't know why you persist in this.

257
00:19:38,589 --> 00:19:43,492
lt's a long voyage, and l hope
that we could find some common interest.

258
00:19:45,596 --> 00:19:48,497
-Do you play the chess, sir?
-l do.

259
00:19:48,833 --> 00:19:51,324
Well, then, we perhaps could have a game.

260
00:19:52,770 --> 00:19:56,831
Mr. Keil, l have neither the time,
nor the desire to play chess with you.

261
00:19:59,243 --> 00:20:00,801
Capt. Mueller...

262
00:20:02,179 --> 00:20:05,171
l'm not accustomed to unfriendliness.

263
00:20:06,117 --> 00:20:07,141
And....

264
00:20:09,487 --> 00:20:12,479
l quite frankly....
l was really not prepared for it.

265
00:20:12,590 --> 00:20:15,753
Do you have some particular quarrel
with SS, Captain?

266
00:20:17,595 --> 00:20:22,089
l'm sure that you SS gentlemen
are very valuable on dry land...

267
00:20:22,466 --> 00:20:24,661
but on this ship l have a job to do.

268
00:20:26,103 --> 00:20:29,664
But how does my being on board this ship
affect your job?

269
00:20:30,141 --> 00:20:34,475
My crew. Word's gotten around that
you're aboard, and they're scared to death.

270
00:20:35,946 --> 00:20:37,436
This is ridiculous.

271
00:20:38,115 --> 00:20:42,518
Ridiculous or not, l shall have to ask you
to confine yourself to your cabin...

272
00:20:42,620 --> 00:20:44,485
the deck, and the salon.

273
00:20:45,356 --> 00:20:48,484
l don't want you to interfere
with their work or mine.

274
00:20:50,194 --> 00:20:51,491
Do you mean....

275
00:20:51,962 --> 00:20:56,558
Am l to understand that l will not be free
to walk around the ship?

276
00:20:56,667 --> 00:20:57,725
Yes, just that.

277
00:20:57,835 --> 00:21:00,395
The Admiralty described you
as a passenger.

278
00:21:00,704 --> 00:21:04,697
So you will have all the privileges
and the restrictions of a passenger.

279
00:21:04,809 --> 00:21:08,745
They failed to describe the captain
as not only foolish but ill-mannered.

280
00:21:08,846 --> 00:21:11,314
-Well, that's their blunder.
-Capt. Mueller...

281
00:21:11,816 --> 00:21:14,751
l don't have to put up
with this sort of rudeness...

282
00:21:14,852 --> 00:21:18,652
and l would like to suggest that you show
a little more respect for me...

283
00:21:18,722 --> 00:21:22,658
for my authority,
and for the organization that l represent.

284
00:21:22,827 --> 00:21:27,093
l am the master of this ship.
You're under my authority here.

285
00:21:33,704 --> 00:21:35,228
Mr. Kruse...

286
00:21:35,606 --> 00:21:40,373
you will attest that the captain
is not only insulting but uncooperative.

287
00:21:41,512 --> 00:21:44,709
l will make a full report of this
when we reach Bordeaux.

288
00:21:44,782 --> 00:21:45,840
Bordeaux?

289
00:21:47,251 --> 00:21:50,448
The only report l care about,
if we reach Bordeaux...

290
00:21:50,888 --> 00:21:52,412
is that Capt. Mueller brought the Ingo...

291
00:21:52,523 --> 00:21:55,458
on a 15,000 mile journey
through enemy waters...

292
00:21:55,559 --> 00:21:58,619
with a precious cargo, successfully.

293
00:21:59,296 --> 00:22:01,856
Even if he didn't play chess on the way.

294
00:22:02,299 --> 00:22:05,200
l hoped that our relations
would be pleasant...

295
00:22:05,803 --> 00:22:09,739
but l see that they won't. Good night.

296
00:22:13,410 --> 00:22:17,210
lf you will allow me also, Captain?
l'm due on the bridge.

297
00:22:18,916 --> 00:22:20,042
Mr. Keil?

298
00:22:23,153 --> 00:22:26,452
-That was outrageous.
-Yeah, perhaps.

299
00:22:26,624 --> 00:22:29,218
-Allow me to apologize for him.
-No, no. You're very kind...

300
00:22:29,293 --> 00:22:31,318
but this is not your concern.

301
00:22:31,629 --> 00:22:35,395
But, anyway, l don't intend to comply.

302
00:22:36,300 --> 00:22:39,269
Unfortunately, Standard Leader,
l must urge you to do as he says.

303
00:22:39,336 --> 00:22:42,669
He is in command until Bordeaux.

304
00:22:43,407 --> 00:22:46,171
Until Bordeaux? Yeah.

305
00:22:46,944 --> 00:22:48,741
-Good night.
-Good night.

306
00:23:25,883 --> 00:23:28,818
-Your watch is on at eight bells.
-All right, sir.

307
00:27:18,081 --> 00:27:21,141
Revolution's 1,200. Steady.

308
00:27:33,897 --> 00:27:38,834
Must have been a rat chewing on a wire.
Not much else to eat on this ship anyhow.

309
00:29:12,929 --> 00:29:14,419
Hello, sir.

310
00:29:14,931 --> 00:29:15,989
What?

311
00:29:17,000 --> 00:29:18,865
l'm looking for my bird.

312
00:29:19,436 --> 00:29:21,028
Are you blind?

313
00:29:27,678 --> 00:29:31,239
-You work in the engine room?
-l'm the Donkeyman, sir.

314
00:29:31,615 --> 00:29:34,846
-Your name is Donkeyman?
-No.

315
00:29:34,951 --> 00:29:37,419
That is what they call the stoker.

316
00:29:37,521 --> 00:29:38,613
Yeah.

317
00:29:39,723 --> 00:29:42,886
l hope my bird isn't disturbing you, sir?

318
00:29:43,760 --> 00:29:44,954
Not at all.

319
00:29:46,863 --> 00:29:50,458
You are one of the men
who was brought on the ship under guard.

320
00:29:50,967 --> 00:29:52,400
Yes, sir.

321
00:29:53,437 --> 00:29:55,530
What is the charge against you?

322
00:29:56,807 --> 00:30:00,766
-l am a political prisoner, sir.
-Political prisoner?

323
00:30:02,612 --> 00:30:04,273
Falsely accused?

324
00:30:08,085 --> 00:30:11,486
No, sir, not falsely accused.

325
00:30:50,827 --> 00:30:53,921
Boat drill! Boat drill! To your stations!

326
00:30:54,798 --> 00:30:57,164
Everybody, to your stations.

327
00:31:39,509 --> 00:31:41,670
lt's time the men knew the truth.

328
00:31:43,013 --> 00:31:44,810
You'll address them after the drill then?

329
00:31:44,881 --> 00:31:47,509
l wouldn't make a speech
at the Föhrer's wedding.

330
00:31:47,584 --> 00:31:49,381
Address them yourself.

331
00:31:50,587 --> 00:31:52,418
Have you seen our passenger?

332
00:31:52,522 --> 00:31:54,353
He's supposed to be at number two.

333
00:31:54,424 --> 00:31:56,915
No, but l'm sure
he can take care of himself.

334
00:31:57,027 --> 00:32:00,360
Oh, l'm sure he can,
but he's supposed to be at his position.

335
00:32:00,864 --> 00:32:03,594
Perhaps he's waiting
for a personal invitation.

336
00:32:13,009 --> 00:32:16,069
-Better get to your station, Dr. Ambach.
-Oh, yeah.

337
00:32:32,629 --> 00:32:34,256
Mr. Keil?

338
00:32:46,376 --> 00:32:47,809
Hold the boats!

339
00:32:47,911 --> 00:32:49,401
Re-stow them !

340
00:32:50,814 --> 00:32:55,046
Officers and crew, assemble on foredeck!

341
00:32:58,154 --> 00:33:00,782
Officers and men,
assemble on the foredeck.

342
00:33:07,297 --> 00:33:08,787
Where have you been?

343
00:33:09,766 --> 00:33:11,734
Attending your boat drill.

344
00:33:12,502 --> 00:33:15,232
Are you telling me
you've been here all along?

345
00:33:15,438 --> 00:33:16,962
Certainly not.

346
00:33:17,440 --> 00:33:22,343
There was no life jacket in my cabin,
so l was obliged to find one for myself.

347
00:33:22,679 --> 00:33:25,113
l managed to locate one in this...

348
00:33:26,082 --> 00:33:29,779
machine shop of yours
which, incidentally, is a filthy hole.

349
00:33:30,487 --> 00:33:33,012
That cabin wasn't
supposed to be occupied.

350
00:33:36,026 --> 00:33:38,859
Well, we're not being torpedoed,
are we, Captain?

351
00:33:39,596 --> 00:33:41,325
lt's just a boat drill.

352
00:33:48,939 --> 00:33:53,603
For security purposes, you had been told
that our destination was the China coast.

353
00:33:54,311 --> 00:33:55,869
That is not the fact.

354
00:33:56,046 --> 00:33:58,947
This voyage, therefore,
will not end in a few days.

355
00:33:59,015 --> 00:34:01,677
lt will require another 80 days.

356
00:34:02,552 --> 00:34:05,112
Journey's end will be a port in France...

357
00:34:05,956 --> 00:34:08,720
occupied gloriously by our countrymen.

358
00:34:09,793 --> 00:34:11,886
From now on, our watches will be armed.

359
00:34:12,562 --> 00:34:14,962
Not the slightest misconduct
will be tolerated!

360
00:34:15,031 --> 00:34:17,499
Thank you, Mr. Kruse. That's fine.

361
00:34:19,669 --> 00:34:24,368
The watches will not be armed.
The First Officer mistook one of my orders.

362
00:34:25,375 --> 00:34:27,741
As to those of you with bad records...

363
00:34:28,545 --> 00:34:32,345
you will toe the line, as we all will.

364
00:34:34,851 --> 00:34:35,977
Dismissed.

365
00:34:40,824 --> 00:34:42,155
But, sir....

366
00:34:42,225 --> 00:34:45,160
l have never captained
a prison ship before...

367
00:34:49,532 --> 00:34:51,762
and don't intend to now.

368
00:35:14,524 --> 00:35:18,290
-How is your insane friend today?
-Fine, sir.

369
00:35:20,730 --> 00:35:22,061
Well...

370
00:35:22,932 --> 00:35:25,366
this is my first voyage on a freighter.

371
00:35:25,535 --> 00:35:27,127
l find it interesting.

372
00:35:28,138 --> 00:35:29,799
Very interesting.

373
00:35:31,474 --> 00:35:33,271
What is this machine here?

374
00:35:33,710 --> 00:35:35,701
-The winch.
-Winch?

375
00:35:35,779 --> 00:35:37,872
The winch for lifting the cargo.

376
00:35:38,381 --> 00:35:41,646
-Oh, yes, this is the cargo hold?
-Yes, sir.

377
00:35:43,253 --> 00:35:46,780
-How do you get in?
-Right from the deck, sir.

378
00:35:47,090 --> 00:35:49,058
Once you get the hatch cover off.

379
00:35:53,329 --> 00:35:56,958
You mean there are
no connecting doorways down below...

380
00:35:57,067 --> 00:35:59,661
-from one cargo hold to the other?
-No, sir.

381
00:36:00,270 --> 00:36:01,965
Not on a freighter, sir.

382
00:36:05,408 --> 00:36:07,000
Better be careful.

383
00:36:09,679 --> 00:36:13,137
One day, this bird of yours might fly away
with a seagull.

384
00:36:24,661 --> 00:36:26,356
l promise you...

385
00:36:26,863 --> 00:36:28,922
before this ship reaches port...

386
00:36:28,998 --> 00:36:31,865
there's going to be one dead
SS bastard on it.

387
00:36:37,841 --> 00:36:39,274
Come in.

388
00:36:40,810 --> 00:36:42,505
Oh, Standard Leader.

389
00:36:43,213 --> 00:36:46,182
-Come in.
-l hope l'm not disturbing.

390
00:36:47,050 --> 00:36:49,109
Certainly not, Standard Leader.

391
00:36:50,553 --> 00:36:53,215
-Take a seat.
-Thank you very much.

392
00:36:54,023 --> 00:36:55,718
Care for a cigarette?

393
00:36:55,825 --> 00:36:59,693
No, l think l won't have a cigarette.

394
00:37:03,166 --> 00:37:04,827
My coming here is a gamble...

395
00:37:04,901 --> 00:37:07,734
but l think l have not made
a mistake about you.

396
00:37:08,905 --> 00:37:12,705
-May l speak directly?
-By all means.

397
00:37:16,146 --> 00:37:20,412
l think that neither you or l are pleased...

398
00:37:21,251 --> 00:37:22,912
with....

399
00:37:27,657 --> 00:37:31,149
l hope you won't be offended
if l ask to see your party card.

400
00:37:32,495 --> 00:37:34,156
-My party card?
-Yeah.

401
00:37:50,046 --> 00:37:52,014
-This is my party card.
-Thank you.

402
00:37:56,219 --> 00:37:58,710
Well, l see you've kept up
your yearly contributions.

403
00:37:58,788 --> 00:37:59,846
Yes.

404
00:38:00,056 --> 00:38:01,114
You know...

405
00:38:01,224 --> 00:38:05,854
what constantly confounds me, is the
irony of careers in the merchant service.

406
00:38:05,929 --> 00:38:09,421
We have a man like Mueller
at the top, and...

407
00:38:09,732 --> 00:38:13,065
while a man like yourself,
a genuine German...

408
00:38:13,403 --> 00:38:15,564
in the best sense of the phrase...

409
00:38:16,239 --> 00:38:18,264
is First Officer.

410
00:38:20,210 --> 00:38:23,702
But l did not knock on your door
to flatter you.

411
00:38:24,214 --> 00:38:25,238
Now...

412
00:38:26,883 --> 00:38:28,783
what is your opinion...

413
00:38:29,552 --> 00:38:32,885
of Capt. Mueller's approach to discipline?

414
00:38:34,257 --> 00:38:35,417
Discipline?

415
00:38:36,960 --> 00:38:40,327
He approaches it
as if we were carrying a cargo of kimonos.

416
00:38:41,764 --> 00:38:44,756
Exactly. Now...

417
00:38:47,170 --> 00:38:50,333
you must realize by now
that l'm not just a passenger.

418
00:38:52,308 --> 00:38:53,775
Certainly.

419
00:38:54,077 --> 00:38:57,808
And l'm not here to count
the bottles of wine that Mueller drinks.

420
00:38:58,281 --> 00:39:01,409
lt is necessary for me
to inspect this ship, all of it.

421
00:39:01,818 --> 00:39:06,278
And l prefer that Capt. Mueller
is not made aware of this or anyone else.

422
00:39:08,024 --> 00:39:09,082
Yes.

423
00:39:09,292 --> 00:39:12,284
And you will be kind enough
to arrange this for me.

424
00:39:16,866 --> 00:39:21,803
Now, l must ask to look
at your party card, Standard Leader.

425
00:39:22,105 --> 00:39:24,471
Please drop the title when we're alone.
lt's....

426
00:39:24,707 --> 00:39:26,140
May l see it?

427
00:39:29,612 --> 00:39:30,670
Here.

428
00:39:31,881 --> 00:39:33,143
You know, l'm...

429
00:39:33,850 --> 00:39:37,047
l'm happy that you asked me this
because if you didn't, l would know...

430
00:39:37,153 --> 00:39:40,680
that you were not being as alert
as you might be.

431
00:39:42,225 --> 00:39:43,487
May l ask...

432
00:39:44,827 --> 00:39:46,727
the purpose of your request?

433
00:39:47,130 --> 00:39:48,461
l am sorry, but...

434
00:39:48,531 --> 00:39:52,865
under the circumstances, l cannot afford
to take anyone into my confidence.

435
00:39:53,036 --> 00:39:54,526
But thank you.

436
00:39:54,637 --> 00:39:58,300
l can tell you this, which is
something that you are already aware of...

437
00:39:58,374 --> 00:40:01,707
and that is that there are
political prisoners on board.

438
00:40:03,846 --> 00:40:06,542
And if l were a political prisoner...

439
00:40:09,585 --> 00:40:14,386
l would not be completely disappointed
if this ship did not reach Bordeaux.

440
00:40:17,060 --> 00:40:19,221
l feel l should oblige you, Mr. Keil...

441
00:40:19,329 --> 00:40:21,991
but to act contrary
to the orders of my superior....

442
00:40:22,231 --> 00:40:26,395
Certainly, l understand, but if you should
feel the need for my support at any time--

443
00:40:26,502 --> 00:40:28,868
l appreciate that very much, but...

444
00:40:30,073 --> 00:40:31,335
l must think it over.

445
00:40:31,407 --> 00:40:34,205
Naturally. This is logical.

446
00:40:34,377 --> 00:40:37,107
But while you think it over,
l would like to remind you...

447
00:40:37,213 --> 00:40:39,113
of our first allegiance.

448
00:40:39,782 --> 00:40:42,012
-HeiI Hitler.
-HeiI Hitler.

449
00:40:42,418 --> 00:40:43,885
-Thank you so much.
-Good night.

450
00:40:43,953 --> 00:40:45,011
Good night.

451
00:41:55,925 --> 00:41:58,587
Mr. Keil? Mr. Keil?

452
00:41:58,694 --> 00:42:01,857
l'm sorry to interrupt you, sir,
but this is impossible for me.

453
00:42:01,964 --> 00:42:04,125
l'm not prepared for a lengthy voyage.

454
00:42:04,200 --> 00:42:06,361
Would you use your influence, sir?

455
00:42:07,603 --> 00:42:09,298
l don't believe l understand.

456
00:42:09,372 --> 00:42:13,331
Well, l have to be returned to Tokyo.
We must put about.

457
00:42:15,144 --> 00:42:18,307
You have a rather
original sense of comedy, Dr. Ambach.

458
00:42:18,481 --> 00:42:22,474
l know l sound absurd,
and l'm sorry to bother you with this...

459
00:42:22,552 --> 00:42:25,851
but l have problems, certain problems.

460
00:42:25,988 --> 00:42:28,548
Dr. Ambach, we all have problems.

461
00:42:28,958 --> 00:42:33,054
But, Mr. Keil,
these are extremely serious problems.

462
00:42:33,396 --> 00:42:34,658
So...

463
00:42:35,164 --> 00:42:37,792
in this case,
l suggest that you swim back...

464
00:42:37,867 --> 00:42:39,960
because it only takes three weeks...

465
00:42:40,036 --> 00:42:42,698
and the water is not cold this time of year.

466
00:42:44,841 --> 00:42:47,639
This is Radio Norddeich,
