485
00:43:45,201 --> 00:43:47,396
Milkereit was always a pessimist...

486
00:43:47,470 --> 00:43:48,801
senior grade.

487
00:43:49,305 --> 00:43:53,105
''lf Adolf Hitler is steering towards war,
he's a lunatic.''

488
00:43:57,647 --> 00:43:59,911
Letter to a lady friend, 1935.

489
00:44:00,950 --> 00:44:02,941
The lady liked to save letters...

490
00:44:03,052 --> 00:44:06,488
and the Gestapo likes to collect
all kinds of odd documents.

491
00:44:07,156 --> 00:44:10,284
l have that report
in your service file, Milkereit.

492
00:44:10,626 --> 00:44:12,821
But l was much younger.

493
00:44:13,429 --> 00:44:15,659
l don't feel that way any longer.

494
00:44:15,765 --> 00:44:19,428
Yeah, just make sure that your change
of heart is permanent, Milkereit.

495
00:44:20,503 --> 00:44:24,439
And in the future, make sure
to take up with less sentimental ladies.

496
00:44:44,860 --> 00:44:47,761
l once knew a girl who sang that song.

497
00:44:48,397 --> 00:44:49,830
A girl back home.

498
00:44:50,666 --> 00:44:51,690
Home.

499
00:44:52,902 --> 00:44:54,460
lt's been almost two years.

500
00:44:54,537 --> 00:44:55,561
Sir?

501
00:44:56,405 --> 00:44:58,134
A message from Tokyo.

502
00:44:59,075 --> 00:45:00,838
Turn that damn radio off.

503
00:45:01,477 --> 00:45:03,809
''Enemy ships reported your vicinity.

504
00:45:03,879 --> 00:45:07,212
''Camouflage your vessel
as British freighter immediately.''

505
00:45:52,228 --> 00:45:54,389
Raise the starboard waist!

506
00:46:07,143 --> 00:46:08,576
Get going.

507
00:46:10,546 --> 00:46:11,740
Kruse?

508
00:46:12,648 --> 00:46:14,980
Come with me. lt's urgent.

509
00:46:15,451 --> 00:46:16,782
What's urgent?

510
00:46:17,720 --> 00:46:20,086
This is an emergency. Come.

511
00:46:23,225 --> 00:46:26,217
-Cornelson! Take over for me here.
-Yes, sir.

512
00:46:32,101 --> 00:46:33,295
Kruse...

513
00:46:34,570 --> 00:46:38,006
l've decided to take you
completely into my confidence.

514
00:46:39,108 --> 00:46:40,575
Sabotage.

515
00:46:43,346 --> 00:46:44,779
Very clever work.

516
00:46:46,349 --> 00:46:49,079
Now l think you'll know
why l am on this ship.

517
00:47:17,880 --> 00:47:21,475
My instructions were to handle this
by myself, but now there is no time.

518
00:47:21,550 --> 00:47:23,950
You say there are 12 of these...

519
00:47:24,053 --> 00:47:25,714
-scuttling charges?
-Yes.

520
00:47:26,222 --> 00:47:27,712
That's sufficient.

521
00:47:28,791 --> 00:47:33,125
Two or three could probably sink the ship,
so we will have to cover them all.

522
00:47:35,631 --> 00:47:36,825
Now...

523
00:47:37,666 --> 00:47:41,295
how many are there in this hold?

524
00:47:41,370 --> 00:47:42,462
Two.

525
00:47:42,571 --> 00:47:43,799
Where are they located?

526
00:47:43,873 --> 00:47:47,673
One is over there,
at the end of this opening.

527
00:47:57,219 --> 00:47:59,346
Run a cable from the aftermast...

528
00:48:01,323 --> 00:48:02,585
to this deck.

529
00:48:02,825 --> 00:48:04,053
Yes, Captain.

530
00:48:18,174 --> 00:48:19,505
The last one's down here.

531
00:48:19,575 --> 00:48:21,008
What is in the barrels here?

532
00:48:21,076 --> 00:48:22,373
-Barrels?
-Yeah.

533
00:48:22,445 --> 00:48:23,503
Lard.

534
00:48:25,181 --> 00:48:26,876
-Lard?
-Yeah.

535
00:48:26,949 --> 00:48:30,077
A few hundred tons from Okinawa...

536
00:48:31,387 --> 00:48:33,548
for making margarine and candles.

537
00:48:36,058 --> 00:48:38,788
We even have a small shipment
of oolong tea.

538
00:48:38,894 --> 00:48:40,293
Thank you.

539
00:48:41,063 --> 00:48:45,261
Now tell me, Kruse, where is the
master switch for these charges located?

540
00:48:45,434 --> 00:48:46,867
ln the wheelhouse.

541
00:48:46,969 --> 00:48:48,732
-ln the wheelhouse?
-Yeah.

542
00:48:49,071 --> 00:48:51,471
Well, then l'm sure,
the Captain has the only key, huh?

543
00:48:51,574 --> 00:48:52,905
Of course.

544
00:48:54,376 --> 00:48:56,901
l think this one
has not been tampered with.

545
00:48:56,979 --> 00:48:58,276
lt's all right.

546
00:48:59,114 --> 00:49:02,777
Twelve charges and the only two damaged
are in the engine room.

547
00:49:04,286 --> 00:49:05,719
The Donkeyman.

548
00:49:06,655 --> 00:49:08,885
-l'll make short work of him.
-No. Wait, wait, wait.

549
00:49:09,225 --> 00:49:12,319
Whoever it is,
we watch them play out their hand.

550
00:49:13,128 --> 00:49:15,460
But the captain ought to be notified.

551
00:49:17,099 --> 00:49:18,464
Certainly not.

552
00:49:20,302 --> 00:49:23,169
Under these circumstances,
everyone is suspect...

553
00:49:23,572 --> 00:49:25,005
even you.

554
00:49:49,498 --> 00:49:51,864
Look here. There's help.

555
00:49:52,201 --> 00:49:56,297
Very fortunate circumstance
to find an alone American ship.

556
00:49:56,772 --> 00:49:57,966
Very.

557
00:50:00,943 --> 00:50:03,673
We have made radio contact
with the Ingo again, Admiral.

558
00:50:03,779 --> 00:50:05,838
She is on course and all is well.

559
00:50:18,961 --> 00:50:22,124
-Where were your ship going?
-Australia.

560
00:50:22,998 --> 00:50:26,525
-What is your occupation?
-l am a surgical aide.

561
00:50:27,336 --> 00:50:29,236
Why were you going to Australia?

562
00:50:29,838 --> 00:50:31,999
l was a member of a medical team.

563
00:50:32,708 --> 00:50:34,403
You were born in Berlin?

564
00:50:35,411 --> 00:50:36,571
Yes.

565
00:50:37,179 --> 00:50:40,012
And your parents, also born in Germany?

566
00:50:40,816 --> 00:50:41,908
Yes.

567
00:50:42,017 --> 00:50:45,680
So a German girl on an enemy vessel.

568
00:50:47,389 --> 00:50:50,222
Whatever gave you the absurd idea
l was German?

569
00:50:50,326 --> 00:50:52,760
lf you're not a German, what then?

570
00:50:54,396 --> 00:50:56,261
l am anti-German.

571
00:51:40,209 --> 00:51:42,200
Captain, luck's still with us.

572
00:51:44,380 --> 00:51:46,575
The fog is coming in a lot thicker.

573
00:51:47,416 --> 00:51:50,943
You know the chantey
of blockade-runners out of Tokyo, Bosun?

574
00:51:51,320 --> 00:51:55,757
Nine days out, all will be fair.
Ten days out, sailor, beware.

575
00:51:56,325 --> 00:51:57,451
Yes, sir.

576
00:51:57,559 --> 00:51:59,254
Captain, the steward
has just made a strudel.

577
00:51:59,328 --> 00:52:01,728
Good. l'd love it with a cup of coffee.

578
00:52:40,302 --> 00:52:42,270
l've had the men go over
the engines again.

579
00:52:42,337 --> 00:52:45,135
Cylinder head pressure's normal,
rev's increasing.

580
00:52:45,207 --> 00:52:47,767
You must be getting very bored, Mr. Keil.

581
00:52:48,110 --> 00:52:51,204
l'm sorry we don't have shuffleboard
or a band.

582
00:52:52,047 --> 00:52:55,016
Well, l've been able
to occupy myself, Captain.

583
00:52:55,484 --> 00:52:58,282
l've been studying
the animal life in my bunk...

584
00:52:59,154 --> 00:53:01,122
and the wind and waves.

585
00:53:01,957 --> 00:53:04,687
Well, the wind and the waves
have been very good to us.

586
00:53:04,793 --> 00:53:08,229
They certainly have.
We're nearly a full day ahead of schedule.

587
00:53:08,330 --> 00:53:10,992
Yeah, and the old tub
is still glued together.

588
00:53:11,066 --> 00:53:13,034
So help me,
l'm beginning to get fond of her.

589
00:53:13,135 --> 00:53:14,159
Sir?

590
00:53:14,403 --> 00:53:17,861
A number of ships.
Two different codes, very strong.

591
00:53:24,646 --> 00:53:26,671
Signals are much stronger, sir.

592
00:53:27,883 --> 00:53:30,750
They might be
a city block away in this porridge.

593
00:53:31,653 --> 00:53:34,053
-Kruse.
-Captain.

594
00:53:35,190 --> 00:53:37,920
-Shadow!
-There! Pinned her, too, Captain.

595
00:53:40,662 --> 00:53:41,720
Englishmen.

596
00:53:41,830 --> 00:53:44,492
lmproved D class of Lambert and Holt.

597
00:53:46,935 --> 00:53:48,266
Englishmen...

598
00:53:49,605 --> 00:53:51,072
like ourselves.

599
00:53:51,607 --> 00:53:53,598
Three ships off port bow!

600
00:53:57,579 --> 00:53:59,012
Convoy!

601
00:54:00,415 --> 00:54:01,848
Convoy...

602
00:54:03,552 --> 00:54:05,543
and we're in the middle of it.

603
00:54:14,029 --> 00:54:15,257
What do we do now, sir?

604
00:54:15,864 --> 00:54:17,195
Mr. Kruse...

605
00:54:17,466 --> 00:54:19,400
20 degrees to starboard.

606
00:54:20,202 --> 00:54:22,363
-Keep parallel to the convoy.
-Yes, sir...

607
00:54:22,437 --> 00:54:24,200
20 degrees to starboard.

608
00:54:26,041 --> 00:54:27,633
We bluff, young man.

609
00:54:28,777 --> 00:54:30,608
And we believe in miracles.

610
00:54:31,046 --> 00:54:32,104
Captain?

611
00:54:34,149 --> 00:54:37,209
Captain, there's a destroyer...

612
00:54:38,453 --> 00:54:40,148
heading straight for us.

613
00:54:40,255 --> 00:54:42,155
American, Benz-class.

614
00:54:43,225 --> 00:54:45,716
Four guns, 10 torpedo tubes.

615
00:54:47,329 --> 00:54:49,263
Makes 36 knots.

616
00:54:49,565 --> 00:54:51,999
Good. Send them a citation.

617
00:55:04,079 --> 00:55:06,445
Captain, it's a matter of minutes.

618
00:55:07,850 --> 00:55:10,080
Mr. Kruse, sound the general alarm.

619
00:55:11,687 --> 00:55:13,279
Don't sound the horn.

620
00:55:13,488 --> 00:55:15,752
He may be on routine sub patrol
and bear off.

621
00:55:15,824 --> 00:55:19,351
All men to stations
except radio, engine room, and bridge.

622
00:55:19,494 --> 00:55:22,327
Sir, radio message received.
Destroyer wants identification.

623
00:55:22,431 --> 00:55:26,197
Tell Mr. Nissen to send,
"British Stonehenge in convoy.''

624
00:55:26,301 --> 00:55:28,428
-And send it slowly and garbled.
-Garbled, sir?

625
00:55:28,503 --> 00:55:29,993
Mr. Nissen knows
the meaning of the word.

626
00:55:30,105 --> 00:55:31,436
-Now move!
-Yes, sir.

627
00:55:31,506 --> 00:55:33,531
And somebody bring me a cigar.

628
00:55:40,515 --> 00:55:41,948
General alarm !

629
00:55:49,858 --> 00:55:52,326
General alarm ! Don't use the horn!

630
00:56:00,836 --> 00:56:02,963
They are bound to see
we are a fake pretty soon.

631
00:56:03,038 --> 00:56:06,064
We'll be sent to a prisoners-of-war camp,
maybe in Hawaii in the sun.

632
00:56:06,174 --> 00:56:08,039
Come on, darling, take us.

633
00:56:08,543 --> 00:56:10,704
Come, take us, darling. Come on.

634
00:56:10,846 --> 00:56:13,974
Donkeyman, what are you waiting for?
Let's go.

635
00:56:14,082 --> 00:56:17,210
First, l've got a piece of business
to take care of.

636
00:56:53,121 --> 00:56:54,383
Eight hundred yards.

637
00:56:56,959 --> 00:56:58,256
Seven hundred.

638
00:56:59,594 --> 00:57:00,856
Six hundred.

639
00:57:05,200 --> 00:57:06,690
Five hundred yards.

640
00:57:08,904 --> 00:57:10,428
Three hundred fifty.

641
00:57:13,475 --> 00:57:15,204
He's changing course.

642
00:57:15,610 --> 00:57:16,736
He's bearing off.

643
00:57:19,881 --> 00:57:21,280
We are getting away with it.

644
00:57:21,383 --> 00:57:23,078
They think we are real.

645
00:57:23,218 --> 00:57:26,984
l don't know what they think,
but it's time somebody lit my cigar.

646
00:58:10,332 --> 00:58:14,098
You there! Hoffman!
Get off the deck and kill the whistle!

647
00:58:21,143 --> 00:58:24,635
Captain, the destroyer has ordered us
to stop immediately for boarding.

648
00:58:24,713 --> 00:58:25,873
Here, sir.

649
00:58:30,852 --> 00:58:33,844
-Mr. Kruse, halt engines.
-Halt engines, sir.

650
00:58:36,224 --> 00:58:38,988
-Halt engines.
-Halt engines.

651
00:58:39,227 --> 00:58:41,058
Engines halting.

652
00:58:41,296 --> 00:58:42,695
Abandon ship.

653
00:58:43,365 --> 00:58:44,627
Abandon ship.

654
00:58:45,667 --> 00:58:47,191
Abandon ship!

655
00:58:47,302 --> 00:58:48,530
Abandon ship!

656
00:58:49,204 --> 00:58:50,671
lnto the boats!

657
00:58:51,073 --> 00:58:54,201
-Are we scuttling, sir?
-Get on. l'll take care of it.

658
00:58:55,710 --> 00:58:57,541
Get in the boats, men!

659
00:59:01,216 --> 00:59:03,150
And hurry up there! Hurry up!

660
00:59:03,418 --> 00:59:04,976
Hold the line!

661
00:59:38,520 --> 00:59:40,010
Capt. Mueller, wait!

662
00:59:40,088 --> 00:59:41,248
Why aren't you in the lifeboat?

663
00:59:41,356 --> 00:59:43,722
Don't throw your life away needlessly.

664
00:59:43,959 --> 00:59:45,517
You're insane.

665
00:59:45,727 --> 00:59:48,457
l'll be over the side as soon as l finish this.

666
00:59:57,639 --> 01:00:00,073
Mr. Kruse, hold the lifeboats.

667
01:00:00,142 --> 01:00:02,372
Everybody, back to stations!

668
01:00:08,383 --> 01:00:10,544
Sir! Sir!

669
01:00:10,819 --> 01:00:13,720
Mr. Branner reports engine room ready.

670
01:00:16,791 --> 01:00:19,555
Full ahead.
Give me everything you can deliver.

671
01:00:21,129 --> 01:00:23,222
-Hard to starboard.
-Hard to starboard.

672
01:00:23,565 --> 01:00:25,430
We'll make for that fog bank.

673
01:00:26,768 --> 01:00:28,793
Maybe we can sneak out of here.

674
01:00:29,971 --> 01:00:32,166
Helmsman, what's your reading?

675
01:00:33,074 --> 01:00:35,099
One, one, zero, sir.

676
01:00:35,443 --> 01:00:36,501
Port two points.

677
01:00:36,611 --> 01:00:38,738
-Port two points, sir.
-Mr. Milkereit? Mr. Kruse?

678
01:00:38,813 --> 01:00:40,576
-Sir.
-Radical change of course.

679
01:00:40,649 --> 01:00:43,083
-Which alternative, sir?
-Put us on course beta.

680
01:00:43,151 --> 01:00:44,175
Yes, sir.

681
01:00:46,588 --> 01:00:47,919
-Mr. Cornelson?
-Yes, sir.

682
01:00:47,989 --> 01:00:50,924
They'll send our description
to every skiff between here and Midway.

683
01:00:50,992 --> 01:00:53,654
Call Bosun to my quarters.
We change camouflage again.

684
01:00:53,762 --> 01:00:54,922
Yes, sir.

685
01:00:57,999 --> 01:01:01,435
-Mr. Keil?
-Yes.

686
01:01:03,972 --> 01:01:05,963
l have misjudged you, Mr. Keil.

687
01:01:06,775 --> 01:01:09,141
l never for one moment thought that...

688
01:01:09,544 --> 01:01:11,671
you might try to save my life.

689
01:01:13,882 --> 01:01:17,716
You gentlemen of the SS don't usually
display the humanity of a sand crab.

690
01:01:17,819 --> 01:01:21,482
Well, to be honest with you,
l couldn't help myself.

691
01:01:34,803 --> 01:01:38,398
Well, gentlemen, was it God
or the Föhrer that brought the fog?

692
01:01:40,008 --> 01:01:42,568
Thank both, and the captain as well.

693
01:01:43,011 --> 01:01:46,037
-l must say, he used his wits.
-Yeah, he was brilliant.

694
01:01:46,147 --> 01:01:47,171
Yeah.

695
01:01:50,652 --> 01:01:53,246
Milkereit, in which direction
are we headed?

696
01:01:53,688 --> 01:01:56,418
Sorry, our course is classified.

697
01:01:59,320 --> 01:02:03,416
Don't you think that perhaps by now
l am an exception to the general rules?

698
01:02:07,361 --> 01:02:12,162
-As navigation officer, l can't allow that--
-Just for once, use a little common sense.

699
01:02:12,500 --> 01:02:14,434
lt's your responsibility, sir.

700
01:02:18,239 --> 01:02:19,365
Mr. Keil...

701
01:02:21,576 --> 01:02:23,339
-this is our present position.
-Yeah.

702
01:02:23,411 --> 01:02:25,936
This was the old course, almost due east.

703
01:02:26,514 --> 01:02:29,381
Now this will be our new course. See?

704
01:02:31,018 --> 01:02:32,042
Yeah.

705
01:02:36,424 --> 01:02:39,416
-ls that coffee over there?
-Yeah.

706
01:02:39,527 --> 01:02:41,222
-Can l have a cup please?
-Of course.

707
01:02:41,295 --> 01:02:42,557
Thank you.

708
01:02:42,630 --> 01:02:45,394
-Do you take sugar?
-One teaspoon full.

709
01:02:48,302 --> 01:02:51,430
-Here's your coffee.
-Oh. Thank you, very kind.

710
01:02:52,640 --> 01:02:57,236
-Yeah, now, this is the new course.
-This is the new course. Yeah.

711
01:02:58,546 --> 01:03:02,380
-But we lose a lot of time this way--
-Oh, yeah, several days.

712
01:03:02,450 --> 01:03:04,213
-You must have dropped your pin.
-No, no.

713
01:03:04,285 --> 01:03:07,277
l never can measure distance on the map.

714
01:03:07,388 --> 01:03:11,586
l was trying to find out
how far it is from here to here.

715
01:03:11,659 --> 01:03:13,149
That's very easy.

716
01:03:13,628 --> 01:03:15,994
Just a moment, from here to here.

717
01:03:16,898 --> 01:03:19,662
lt's 220 miles.

718
01:03:21,102 --> 01:03:25,061
You know, it's strange.
lt's only about two inches, and yet it's...

719
01:03:25,173 --> 01:03:29,337
-further than Leipzig to Dösseldorf?
-Yeah, you're right.

720
01:03:32,947 --> 01:03:35,108
This island, it's not....

721
01:03:35,983 --> 01:03:39,441
-lt's not dangerous to go so close?
-No, it's uninhabited.

722
01:03:39,821 --> 01:03:42,790
lt's no tactical value for us
or the Americans.

723
01:03:45,660 --> 01:03:48,823
lt has such a strange shape.
lt's like a starfish.

724
01:03:50,932 --> 01:03:54,527
-What are you laughing for?
-That's its name. Starfish lsland.

725
01:03:56,671 --> 01:03:57,933
Yeah, l guess.

726
01:03:58,673 --> 01:04:01,540
This is certainly interesting. l've never...

727
01:04:03,711 --> 01:04:07,169
seen it before.
Kruse, would you excuse me, please?

728
01:04:07,248 --> 01:04:09,580
-l'll see you a bit later.
-Sure, sure. Thank you.

729
01:04:28,936 --> 01:04:30,597
Standard Leader?

730
01:04:37,712 --> 01:04:39,270
Standard Leader.

731
01:04:42,283 --> 01:04:43,409
All right.

732
01:04:44,185 --> 01:04:45,880
Shall we go to my room?

733
01:04:46,420 --> 01:04:47,887
Mine's right here.

734
01:05:05,806 --> 01:05:07,398
Your swindle is over.

735
01:05:08,242 --> 01:05:09,470
What swindle?

736
01:05:10,111 --> 01:05:13,740
lt's damn plain that you don't want
this ship to reach Bordeaux.

737
01:05:20,554 --> 01:05:22,078
What do you want of me?

738
01:05:22,156 --> 01:05:24,716
We want to hear what you've got to offer.

739
01:05:25,159 --> 01:05:27,127
And if we don't like it...

740
01:05:27,628 --> 01:05:30,222
we turn this over to Kruse or the captain.

741
01:05:34,969 --> 01:05:36,163
Milkereit.

742
01:05:37,338 --> 01:05:40,466
-How many are there of you?
-We have four others.

743
01:05:41,342 --> 01:05:43,503
-Four. And there are no officers?
-No.

744
01:05:46,614 --> 01:05:49,344
How long have you been together
with these men?

745
01:05:49,951 --> 01:05:54,183
We started to talk during the camouflage.
And then l saw you jam the whistle...

746
01:05:54,288 --> 01:05:57,018
and realized you also were in the fight
against Hitler.

747
01:05:57,124 --> 01:05:59,456
l see l am surrounded by patriots.

748
01:05:59,961 --> 01:06:01,087
Not these others.

749
01:06:01,162 --> 01:06:03,596
lf they reach Germany,
they will be finished.

750
01:06:03,664 --> 01:06:06,155
Yeah, l think you will be finished also.

751
01:06:07,668 --> 01:06:08,828
Yes, l know.

752
01:06:09,170 --> 01:06:12,799
l keep wondering if that's why
l was assigned here on this ship.

753
01:06:12,974 --> 01:06:15,602
We all have the same goal,
to keep our heads on our shoulders.

754
01:06:16,711 --> 01:06:21,478
Every time we bump into each other,
it's near a scuttling charge. Am l right?

755
01:06:21,549 --> 01:06:24,211
Yeah, l was trying to disarm them.

756
01:06:24,819 --> 01:06:27,219
-What's your plan?
-Now there's no plan.

757
01:06:27,655 --> 01:06:30,954
Before we changed course, we were
headed straight for an Allied ambush.

758
01:06:31,025 --> 01:06:32,049
An ambush?

759
01:06:32,159 --> 01:06:36,186
Yeah, there were American warships
waiting for us, but now it's finished.

760
01:06:38,099 --> 01:06:41,034
-What is your plan?
-We haven't any plan.

761
01:06:42,670 --> 01:06:44,604
There's only one chance then.

762
01:06:44,672 --> 01:06:46,867
This island, Star something.

763
01:06:47,341 --> 01:06:50,208
-Starfish lsland?
-Starfish lsland. How far is it?

764
01:06:51,178 --> 01:06:52,611
About 3,000 miles.

765
01:06:53,481 --> 01:06:54,709
How many days?

766
01:06:55,649 --> 01:06:57,048
Roughly 15 days.

767
01:06:57,885 --> 01:06:58,943
Fifteen.

768
01:07:00,654 --> 01:07:03,054
How close do we come to it
when we pass?

769
01:07:04,658 --> 01:07:06,990
About 70 or 80 miles.

770
01:07:14,402 --> 01:07:15,528
Milkereit!

771
01:07:19,306 --> 01:07:21,331
-Milkereit!
-Just a second, sir.

772
01:07:26,313 --> 01:07:29,578
Excuse me, sir, l was just lying down.

773
01:07:31,318 --> 01:07:32,683
That's all right.

774
01:07:32,753 --> 01:07:35,984
Milkereit, what l need is a report
of all the winds and currents...

775
01:07:36,057 --> 01:07:37,752
of the new course beta.

776
01:07:38,159 --> 01:07:40,719
-As soon as possible.
-Yes, l will do it.

777
01:07:42,897 --> 01:07:43,921
-Okay?
-Yes.

778
01:07:52,673 --> 01:07:54,368
Would it be possible...

779
01:07:56,210 --> 01:07:57,677
when we pass this island...

780
01:07:57,745 --> 01:08:01,112
to take one of those rubber boats
and put it over the side?

781
01:08:01,348 --> 01:08:04,010
-lf it's night.
-And nobody sees us.

782
01:08:04,085 --> 01:08:07,054
The chances of making the island
would still be 15-to-1 .

783
01:08:07,121 --> 01:08:09,589
We must take whatever chance we have.

784
01:08:10,291 --> 01:08:14,125
Now, there are three scuttling charges
that l have not yet disarmed.

785
01:08:14,228 --> 01:08:16,719
l will continue to disarm the charges...

786
01:08:16,797 --> 01:08:19,789
in the events that we are intercepted
by an Allied warship.

787
01:08:19,900 --> 01:08:21,731
Now, are we all agreed?

788
01:08:26,440 --> 01:08:27,600
Yes, we do.

789
01:09:13,287 --> 01:09:15,278
Stop engines. Slow us down.

790
01:09:15,456 --> 01:09:17,856
Stop engines. Slow us down, sir.

791
01:09:18,459 --> 01:09:21,292
-Lower the gangplank.
-Lower the gangplank, sir.

792
01:09:26,433 --> 01:09:28,924
-Lower the gangplank!
-All you men here...

793
01:09:29,203 --> 01:09:30,636
lower the gangway.

794
01:09:53,327 --> 01:09:55,352
Hurry up! Get it over with!

795
01:10:01,669 --> 01:10:05,833
We'll continue to observe radio silence
until after transfer of prisoners.

796
01:10:06,006 --> 01:10:09,134
-What transfer of prisoners?
-Shall l send a reply, sir?

797
01:10:09,510 --> 01:10:12,570
Yes. Tell them Capt. Mueller
just jumped overboard.

798
01:10:54,288 --> 01:10:57,121
-Did you disarm it?
-Yeah, there are only two left.

799
01:11:17,211 --> 01:11:19,076
Welcome aboard the steam ship Christina.

800
01:11:19,146 --> 01:11:20,545
Thank you, Captain.

801
01:11:20,614 --> 01:11:23,640
lt's always nice to meet
an honest Swedish skipper.

802
01:11:24,151 --> 01:11:28,087
You must enjoy being a neutral.
You're lit up like a Christmas tree.

803
01:11:28,155 --> 01:11:29,417
Well, l'm glad l'm no longer English.

804
01:11:29,490 --> 01:11:32,482
You came within 100 yards
of putting a torpedo in my belly.

805
01:11:32,593 --> 01:11:36,120
And your destroyers almost put
a depth charge down my throat.

806
01:11:36,497 --> 01:11:38,488
-Back to stations.
-Back to stations, sir.

807
01:11:38,599 --> 01:11:40,499
Back to stations! Everybody!

808
01:11:44,672 --> 01:11:48,130
l can certainly see why you were
so obstinate back in Japan.

809
01:11:48,475 --> 01:11:52,844
l now hand you custody of 15 prisoners.
lnterrogation report on each.

810
01:11:53,314 --> 01:11:55,145
As well as one on the girl.

811
01:11:55,949 --> 01:11:57,439
Nothing is spared me.

812
01:11:57,518 --> 01:11:59,782
You will find that one very interesting.

813
01:11:59,853 --> 01:12:01,946
-Mr. Kruse?
-Captain.

814
01:12:02,022 --> 01:12:04,183
Escort the prisoners
to twin decks number five.

815
01:12:04,291 --> 01:12:06,020
Yes, sir. Move!

816
01:12:07,361 --> 01:12:08,623
Just a minute.

817
01:12:09,930 --> 01:12:13,422
Mr. Cornelson, you certainly wouldn't
put her up with them.

818
01:12:13,667 --> 01:12:17,103
Mr. Cornelson, take her to my cabin
for the time being.

819
01:12:17,438 --> 01:12:18,666
Now, Adm. Wendel--

820
01:12:18,772 --> 01:12:22,003
l know. l know.
This new cargo is a burden, Captain.

821
01:12:22,209 --> 01:12:24,040
l suppose that's why
you radioed the request...

822
01:12:24,144 --> 01:12:25,771
but not the reason for this rendezvous.

823
01:12:25,846 --> 01:12:28,474
Were you afraid
l might get a bit too obstinate this time?

824
01:12:28,549 --> 01:12:31,279
We thought of that Mueller,
we thought of that.

825
01:12:32,653 --> 01:12:35,520
Now that you're here,
would you join me for a drink?

826
01:12:35,789 --> 01:12:36,949
Fine.

827
01:12:37,458 --> 01:12:40,621
l wouldn't have missed this chance
to congratulate you personally.

828
01:12:40,694 --> 01:12:44,152
Slipping in and out of that convoy.
Remarkable seamanship.

829
01:12:44,231 --> 01:12:45,357
Thank you.

830
01:12:45,699 --> 01:12:49,499
Very gratifying for a captain
who has to have a keeper on his tail.

831
01:12:50,971 --> 01:12:51,995
Keeper?

832
01:12:52,673 --> 01:12:54,834
lnsist on playing games? Very well.

833
01:12:55,142 --> 01:12:57,508
The passenger you gentlemen put aboard.

834
01:13:00,514 --> 01:13:02,209
Someone we put aboard?

835
01:13:03,217 --> 01:13:04,411
HeiI Hitler.

836
01:13:05,152 --> 01:13:06,744
-HeiI Hitler.
-HeiI Hitler.

837
01:13:06,854 --> 01:13:08,685
Adm. Wendel, Cmdr. Busch...

838
01:13:08,989 --> 01:13:12,755
this is my passenger, Mr. Hans Keil
of the Security Office.

839
01:13:12,860 --> 01:13:15,192
Adm. Wendel, it's a pleasure to meet you.

840
01:13:15,262 --> 01:13:16,752
l am delighted, Mr. Keil,
to meet you here.

841
01:13:16,830 --> 01:13:17,854
Thank you.

842
01:13:17,931 --> 01:13:19,159
Glad to meet you.

843
01:13:19,233 --> 01:13:22,225
Your department didn't notify me
of your assignment.

844
01:13:23,170 --> 01:13:25,331
Oh, that's strange.

845
01:13:25,406 --> 01:13:27,374
l presented my credentials
to the embassy.

846
01:13:27,441 --> 01:13:31,844
Naturally. Well, then, your venture
was authorized after l left Tokyo.

847
01:13:32,713 --> 01:13:34,180
Yeah, perhaps.

848
01:13:35,249 --> 01:13:39,686
Anyway, this is not a venture.
l'm just here as a passenger.

849
01:13:39,953 --> 01:13:41,887
-Please, sit down.
-Thank you.

850
01:13:42,689 --> 01:13:45,749
Where were you before Tokyo?

851
01:13:47,895 --> 01:13:49,954
l'm not able to reveal this.

852
01:13:50,798 --> 01:13:52,766
Secret information, no doubt.

853
01:13:54,301 --> 01:13:55,461
Classified.

854
01:13:57,237 --> 01:13:58,363
Gentlemen.

855
01:14:03,977 --> 01:14:05,774
l'll wager one thing.

856
01:14:06,547 --> 01:14:07,605
When you left port...

857
01:14:07,714 --> 01:14:11,980
you didn't expect to run into
two officers from the German Admiralty.

858
01:14:12,653 --> 01:14:14,450
Never hoped for such luck.

859
01:14:16,290 --> 01:14:18,417
Well, as my friend
Bernhard Weber used to say...

860
01:14:18,492 --> 01:14:21,086
if you can't imagine a situation it is....

861
01:14:22,062 --> 01:14:24,121
You knew Brigade Leader Weber?

862
01:14:25,098 --> 01:14:26,463
-Weber?
-From SS leadership school.

863
01:14:26,567 --> 01:14:28,125
You went there, of course.

864
01:14:28,235 --> 01:14:30,829
Yeah, sure, class of 1938.

865
01:14:31,505 --> 01:14:34,065
General Ordenlichter
was the commandant then.

866
01:14:34,741 --> 01:14:36,641
Are you acquainted with him?

867
01:14:36,944 --> 01:14:40,004
-Yes.
-He was a wonderful man.

868
01:14:40,347 --> 01:14:41,780
Class of '38.

869
01:14:43,283 --> 01:14:45,581
Well, then you must know
Brigade Leader Weber.

870
01:14:45,652 --> 01:14:47,779
The Chief of Political Evaluation.

871
01:14:50,190 --> 01:14:51,248
Weber. Weber.

872
01:14:53,093 --> 01:14:54,856
Yeah, l remember him.

873
01:14:59,600 --> 01:15:02,000
l see you smoke an English briar.

874
01:15:03,103 --> 01:15:05,037
An amazing observation.

875
01:15:05,372 --> 01:15:07,772
You should be in counter-intelligence.

876
01:15:08,609 --> 01:15:09,633
l am.

877
01:15:10,344 --> 01:15:12,972
-Really?
-And frankly...

878
01:15:14,047 --> 01:15:16,106
what we would like to determine is...

879
01:15:16,183 --> 01:15:18,378
what you're doing onboard this ship.

880
01:15:19,853 --> 01:15:21,980
Nothing more important than...

881
01:15:22,689 --> 01:15:24,122
being a passenger.

882
01:15:24,858 --> 01:15:27,520
But l'm so flattered with your interest.

883
01:15:29,396 --> 01:15:32,627
Well, l never did finish my remark
about Brigade Leader Weber.

884
01:15:32,699 --> 01:15:35,463
-The Political Evaluation Chief.
-Right.

885
01:15:37,905 --> 01:15:40,533
An astonishing fact is
that he doesn't exist.

886
01:15:41,808 --> 01:15:43,298
l invented the man.

887
01:15:53,587 --> 01:15:55,418
Of course, he doesn't exist.

888
01:15:56,924 --> 01:15:59,757
Gentlemen, l don't wish
to embarrass you...

889
01:15:59,860 --> 01:16:04,695
but really this kind of
interrogation technique is childish.

890
01:16:06,366 --> 01:16:09,824
We learned this in the first two weeks
of leadership school.

891
01:16:10,037 --> 01:16:12,665
But l am fascinated by your curiosity.

892
01:16:12,940 --> 01:16:17,172
You would be less fascinated if l told you
that perhaps you, too, are an invention...

893
01:16:17,444 --> 01:16:20,004
-Standard Leader Keil.
-Now, gentlemen...

894
01:16:20,347 --> 01:16:24,044
if it wasn't for Mr. Keil,
we wouldn't be aboard this ship.

895
01:16:24,551 --> 01:16:27,418
He stopped me from scuttling her.
l had my hand on the switch...

896
01:16:27,521 --> 01:16:29,921
and Mr. Keil thought
that l was going to stay with her...

897
01:16:30,023 --> 01:16:31,581
and did his best to stop me.

898
01:16:31,692 --> 01:16:34,354
And while he was doing that,
your wolf-pack...

899
01:16:34,861 --> 01:16:36,351
blasted the convoy.

900
01:16:36,430 --> 01:16:39,092
So, you see, if he hadn't delayed me
for a few seconds...

901
01:16:39,199 --> 01:16:43,135
7,000 tons of precious rubber
would have been at the bottom of the sea.

902
01:16:43,604 --> 01:16:47,199
So Mr. Keil is capable
of a nice, sentimental gesture.

903
01:16:48,442 --> 01:16:51,707
-That doesn't clear up my doubts.
-l see no reasons...

904
01:16:52,446 --> 01:16:55,779
to discuss matters that concern
only my department.

905
01:16:56,617 --> 01:17:00,314
And now, Adm. Wendel,
let me notify you in very simple terms.

906
01:17:01,455 --> 01:17:04,891
The Security Office will be informed
in every exact detail...

907
01:17:04,958 --> 01:17:07,392
as to your interference, is that clear?

908
01:17:07,561 --> 01:17:10,155
-Mr. Keil, l will not permit you--
-Now, gentlemen.

909
01:17:10,263 --> 01:17:13,790
There is no real problem.
All you have to do is radio Berlin.

910
01:17:17,738 --> 01:17:19,899
Yeah, excellent idea.

911
01:17:24,978 --> 01:17:27,276
This is logical.

912
01:17:38,625 --> 01:17:42,083
Capt. Mueller, are you willing
to be answerable for Mr. Keil?

913
01:17:42,295 --> 01:17:43,319
Yes.

914
01:17:47,000 --> 01:17:48,433
l'll accept that.

915
01:17:49,302 --> 01:17:51,634
l don't think we need trouble Berlin.

916
01:17:51,705 --> 01:17:53,969
l realize that we have offended you.

917
01:17:54,174 --> 01:17:57,439
But you must understand
our need for caution.

918
01:17:57,711 --> 01:17:59,440
lf l didn't, who would?

919
01:17:59,646 --> 01:18:01,671
At any rate, my regrets.

920
01:18:02,716 --> 01:18:03,978
Adm. Wendel.

921
01:18:04,818 --> 01:18:07,480
And thank you
for your excellent hospitality.

922
01:18:08,455 --> 01:18:09,945
Good night, Mr. Keil.

923
01:18:17,330 --> 01:18:19,798
Naturally, l'll radio Berlin.

924
01:18:20,300 --> 01:18:23,292
By this time tomorrow,
you should have a complete report.

925
01:18:23,370 --> 01:18:26,533
Meantime, keep an eye on him.

926
01:18:49,930 --> 01:18:53,889
Capt. Mueller, thank you for your gesture.
lt was very kind.

927
01:18:54,267 --> 01:18:57,031
You gentlemen wouldn't trust
your own embalmer.

928
01:18:57,504 --> 01:19:00,530
Enjoy your next 24 hours.
They may be your last ones.

929
01:19:01,908 --> 01:19:03,876
They're checking with Berlin.

930
01:19:15,222 --> 01:19:18,623
Did the officer who brought you here
ask your name?

931
01:19:19,559 --> 01:19:21,083
-No.
-Good.

932
01:19:22,863 --> 01:19:25,354
You must promise
to keep your mouth shut.

933
01:19:26,133 --> 01:19:28,260
Keep my mouth shut about what?

934
01:19:31,271 --> 01:19:33,205
About the fact that you're....

935
01:19:33,740 --> 01:19:34,764
A Jewess?

936
01:19:35,642 --> 01:19:37,872
ls it so difficult to say the word?

937
01:19:41,248 --> 01:19:44,149
l have nothing against you
because you are Jewish.

938
01:19:44,785 --> 01:19:46,912
One can't choose one's parents.

939
01:19:46,987 --> 01:19:50,047
-ls that what you mean?
-No, that is not what l mean.

940
01:19:51,391 --> 01:19:52,415
Sit down.

941
01:19:55,128 --> 01:19:56,152
Sit down!

942
01:20:05,672 --> 01:20:06,934
That's my son.

943
01:20:08,008 --> 01:20:09,270
He'd like you.

944
01:20:10,410 --> 01:20:13,470
On the other hand, he might prefer
to lop off my head.

945
01:20:15,182 --> 01:20:17,810
Why do you resent being treated
with respect?

946
01:20:21,154 --> 01:20:23,782
Let's see. Your name: ''Esther Levy.''

947
01:20:24,825 --> 01:20:27,191
Levy won't do. What shall we call you?

948
01:20:27,761 --> 01:20:29,626
Cohen? Shapiro?

949
01:20:30,363 --> 01:20:34,197
Look, there's a long trip ahead.
Put a lid on your pride.

950
01:20:34,768 --> 01:20:36,702
lt's worth it to make yourself comfortable.

951
01:20:36,803 --> 01:20:38,668
And let you feel decent.

952
01:20:40,273 --> 01:20:41,467
lf you wish.

953
01:20:44,044 --> 01:20:45,875
Then lend me a needle and thread.

954
01:20:45,979 --> 01:20:48,277
l'd like to make this outfit
a little more attractive...

955
01:20:48,348 --> 01:20:50,179
for the concentration camp.

956
01:20:55,822 --> 01:20:57,551
When we reach Bordeaux...

957
01:20:59,459 --> 01:21:01,222
this report will be lost.

958
01:21:09,069 --> 01:21:10,468
And with luck...

959
01:21:11,137 --> 01:21:14,573
perhaps you may find a way
to lose yourself there, too.

960
01:21:17,344 --> 01:21:19,574
l'm sorry. lt's the most l can do.

961
01:21:24,551 --> 01:21:26,519
Do you want to sleep with me?

962
01:21:30,423 --> 01:21:33,586
Or you're just doing this
because you're kindhearted?

963
01:21:36,696 --> 01:21:39,995
Young lady, even this kind
of impudence will not stop me...

964
01:21:40,066 --> 01:21:43,661
from treating you simply
as another member of the human race.

965
01:21:51,111 --> 01:21:52,237
All right.

966
01:21:54,047 --> 01:21:58,006
ln America, l lived
with a family named Goddard.

967
01:21:59,619 --> 01:22:03,282
Milkereit, since you are on the bridge,
you can take the captain by surprise.

968
01:22:03,390 --> 01:22:05,790
-Alone?
-No, Boeck will be with you.

969
01:22:06,559 --> 01:22:10,723
Donkeyman, you and Hoffman
will overpower the guard on the rear deck.

970
01:22:10,964 --> 01:22:13,023
But how do we get
those prisoners with us?

971
01:22:13,099 --> 01:22:16,466
Well, l will have to find a way
to speak with them as soon as possible.

972
01:22:16,569 --> 01:22:19,060
l would first like to consider
all the risks before making--

973
01:22:19,139 --> 01:22:20,629
There is nothing to consider.

974
01:22:20,740 --> 01:22:23,766
Consider how your face will look
with a piano wire around your neck...

975
01:22:23,877 --> 01:22:26,573
when Kruse sends his report
into the Gestapo.

976
01:22:29,115 --> 01:22:31,811
But without those prisoners,
we have no chance.

977
01:22:31,952 --> 01:22:33,442
Not even with them.

978
01:22:34,454 --> 01:22:39,050
lf we take over the ship, we are only
two days away from the American navy.

979
01:22:42,429 --> 01:22:45,057
You know what looks
very good to me now?

980
01:22:46,800 --> 01:22:48,233
Starfish lsland.

981
01:22:50,403 --> 01:22:51,597
Donkeyman...

982
01:22:52,973 --> 01:22:55,635
you said the odds against
this island were...

983
01:22:55,809 --> 01:22:57,299
what, 15-to-1?

984
01:22:57,777 --> 01:22:59,836
What are they against this plan?

985
01:23:01,081 --> 01:23:02,412
14-to-1 .

986
01:23:05,418 --> 01:23:07,249
We must make a decision.

987
01:23:08,788 --> 01:23:10,085
Yes.

988
01:23:11,091 --> 01:23:12,115
Let's go.

989
01:23:20,133 --> 01:23:22,124
Miss Goddard, this is...

990
01:23:23,003 --> 01:23:24,595
Standard Leader Keil.

991
01:23:24,971 --> 01:23:25,995
How do you do?

992
01:23:26,306 --> 01:23:29,207
Miss Goddard is an American girl.
She studied in Germany.

993
01:23:29,876 --> 01:23:32,367
Well, we are delighted
to have you with us.

994
01:23:37,851 --> 01:23:40,319
ls it my insignia that disturbs her?

995
01:23:42,389 --> 01:23:45,119
-Captain, where is my room?
-Right here.

996
01:23:47,494 --> 01:23:51,521
lt's obvious that you share
the captain's sentiments about the SS.

997
01:23:52,332 --> 01:23:55,893
As l told Capt. Mueller,
it was a long voyage.

998
01:23:58,571 --> 01:23:59,629
Yes.

999
01:24:00,640 --> 01:24:03,507
Chess partners are very difficult
to come by Mr. Keil.

1000
01:24:03,576 --> 01:24:04,702
Evidently.

1001
01:24:23,496 --> 01:24:24,724
Miss Goddard?

1002
01:24:26,099 --> 01:24:28,567
-Miss Goddard?
-Who is it?

1003
01:24:28,668 --> 01:24:31,364
lt's Mr. Keil.
Could l speak with you one moment?

1004
01:24:31,538 --> 01:24:33,597
There is a crack under the door.

1005
01:24:33,840 --> 01:24:36,673
lt should be easy
for you to crawl through it.

1006
01:24:40,447 --> 01:24:43,348
At 7:00 every morning,
an officer and two crew members...

1007
01:24:43,416 --> 01:24:45,350
will supervise the prisoners exercise.

1008
01:24:45,418 --> 01:24:48,353
After this duty, the weapons
will be locked in the ordinance room.

1009
01:24:48,788 --> 01:24:52,417
Now l understand the hatch covers over
the prisoners hold were closed last night.

1010
01:24:52,525 --> 01:24:54,425
You must like steam baths.

1011
01:24:54,527 --> 01:24:56,893
From now on, the hatch covers
will remain partially open...

1012
01:24:56,963 --> 01:25:00,364
and therefore, the regular watch
in the area will be armed.

1013
01:25:01,301 --> 01:25:05,431
l acted for our well-being, sir,
not towards the enemy's.

1014
01:25:06,739 --> 01:25:10,607
Well, l won't let it spoil my appetite
for breakfast.

1015
01:25:11,077 --> 01:25:12,704
l'm glad of that, sir.

1016
01:25:38,638 --> 01:25:42,005
There's international rules!
We got a right to be heard.

1017
01:25:42,108 --> 01:25:44,076
Shall we arrange it for them?

1018
01:25:48,181 --> 01:25:49,808
l would like to be there...

1019
01:25:49,916 --> 01:25:53,317
when you try to convince
these birds to join the Gestapo.

1020
01:25:56,990 --> 01:26:00,084
Some day it will be a pleasure
to pay a visit to America.

1021
01:26:00,160 --> 01:26:03,755
-This will be wonderful.
-Meanwhile, let's eat. Thank you.

1022
01:26:05,698 --> 01:26:07,598
Keep moving. Let's go.

1023
01:26:10,770 --> 01:26:13,261
Keep moving! Call Dr. Ambach.

1024
01:26:13,439 --> 01:26:16,772
Take him over to the hospital right away.
You, follow them.

1025
01:26:18,645 --> 01:26:23,446
Captain, emergency! A prisoner's hurt.
We can't rouse Dr. Ambach.

1026
01:26:25,718 --> 01:26:27,276
Get me the morphine.

1027
01:26:35,795 --> 01:26:38,855
lt's bad, but not as bad
as the racket you're making.

1028
01:26:40,033 --> 01:26:42,968
-What's the matter?
-There's no morphine here.

1029
01:26:46,472 --> 01:26:47,666
l'll get it.

1030
01:26:53,713 --> 01:26:56,580
You can be of use. Go up there and help.

1031
01:27:18,271 --> 01:27:21,570
You, up here. Us, sweating in a dungeon.

1032
01:27:21,774 --> 01:27:24,766
-Your kind always wind up living rich.
-Shut up.

1033
01:27:25,411 --> 01:27:28,574
Shut up, you crackpot.
We're sick of hearing that garbage.

1034
01:27:28,681 --> 01:27:30,672
What's this? What do you mean?

1035
01:27:30,883 --> 01:27:32,578
He means l'm a Jew.

1036
01:27:36,422 --> 01:27:38,447
Where do you hide the ship's morphine?

1037
01:27:38,558 --> 01:27:42,585
-This damn fever gets me now.
-Where is the morphine, Mr. Ambach?

1038
01:27:43,062 --> 01:27:46,520
Morphine? There is no morphine.

1039
01:27:51,037 --> 01:27:54,404
No, no, no. lt's mine.

1040
01:27:54,741 --> 01:27:58,370
l brought it aboard the ship myself.
lt's mine. This stuff's mine.

1041
01:27:58,444 --> 01:28:02,642
lt's private property. No!
You can't have that. Captain!

1042
01:28:02,749 --> 01:28:04,740
l'll die without it. l'll die.

1043
01:28:05,218 --> 01:28:06,879
You'll live, Mr. Ambach.

1044
01:28:09,656 --> 01:28:13,057
They told me voyage to China coast...

1045
01:28:13,660 --> 01:28:15,059
only a few days.

1046
01:28:16,095 --> 01:28:17,562
They lied to me.

1047
01:28:18,464 --> 01:28:21,661
l had to take it. l had to take it.

1048
01:28:22,568 --> 01:28:23,592
l had to.

1049
01:28:40,987 --> 01:28:43,012
Do you want me to clean it now?

1050
01:28:43,156 --> 01:28:46,648
When a Jewish bitch takes over
the sick ward then....

1051
01:28:47,193 --> 01:28:50,128
Miss Levy is perfectly able
to attend to this.

1052
01:28:52,131 --> 01:28:53,621
Miss Levy?

1053
01:28:54,534 --> 01:28:55,933
You knew.

1054
01:28:56,869 --> 01:28:59,133
Have you thought of the effect
on the officers and men?

1055
01:28:59,205 --> 01:29:01,639
l didn't know it was contagious.

1056
01:29:02,575 --> 01:29:04,975
Now, what do you have to say about this?

1057
01:29:05,845 --> 01:29:07,142
l think you're out of your mind...

1058
01:29:07,246 --> 01:29:09,077
but, after all,
you are the master of the ship.

1059
01:29:09,148 --> 01:29:10,342
That l am.

1060
01:29:11,317 --> 01:29:14,650
Now, take care of it.
l'm sure you can do it better than l can.

1061
01:29:20,693 --> 01:29:23,526
You're saying that she will continue
to have a stage room?

1062
01:29:23,629 --> 01:29:25,597
That you will go on feeding her
in the salon?

1063
01:29:25,665 --> 01:29:27,292
The lady's privileges will remain.

1064
01:29:27,367 --> 01:29:30,097
Now the steward will be glad
to serve your meals in your cabin...

1065
01:29:30,169 --> 01:29:31,261
if it's all too much for you.

1066
01:29:31,337 --> 01:29:34,636
-l must remind you of the consequences.
-l recognize that word.

1067
01:29:34,707 --> 01:29:37,608
lf all Germans had conducted
themselves like this...

1068
01:29:37,677 --> 01:29:40,805
-where do you suppose we'd be today?
-Certainly not where we are now.

1069
01:29:40,880 --> 01:29:43,974
-You are speaking to a party member.
-This is not a party office.

1070
01:29:44,050 --> 01:29:46,644
You had better remember
there's nothing chalked up against me.

1071
01:29:46,719 --> 01:29:49,313
-Now don't you carry me--
-Not even an ounce of Jamaican rum.

1072
01:29:49,389 --> 01:29:50,515
Now you listen to me!

1073
01:29:50,623 --> 01:29:53,456
l've been at sea too long for this.
l know all your talk.

1074
01:29:53,526 --> 01:29:57,519
l'll take the responsibility for what l do.
You young men...

1075
01:29:59,499 --> 01:30:01,490
who keep the world breathless.

1076
01:30:02,869 --> 01:30:04,860
lt's your time, l know.

1077
01:30:06,906 --> 01:30:09,636
But to realize your dreams...

1078
01:30:10,710 --> 01:30:13,304
you'll need something more than brutality.

1079
01:30:15,081 --> 01:30:17,879
You'll need, if you can manage it,
a little mercy.

1080
01:30:17,984 --> 01:30:20,384
Now, what could you know of our dreams?

1081
01:30:35,735 --> 01:30:37,430
l'm all right now. Thanks.

1082
01:30:55,354 --> 01:30:56,548
l'm not going to hurt you.

1083
01:30:56,622 --> 01:30:58,385
l'm not going to hurt you. Listen.

1084
01:30:58,458 --> 01:31:00,016
Just listen and be quiet.

1085
01:31:00,092 --> 01:31:02,959
lf you scream,
you will only place your life in danger.

1086
01:31:03,062 --> 01:31:05,030
Now, understand that l'm not an SS man.

1087
01:31:05,097 --> 01:31:07,429
l am a German,
working for the British lntelligence...

1088
01:31:07,533 --> 01:31:09,558
and l am planning to take over this ship.

1089
01:31:09,635 --> 01:31:11,933
Now, l am going to take my hands away
from your mouth...

1090
01:31:12,038 --> 01:31:14,632
and l don't want you to scream.
Don't scream.

1091
01:31:18,377 --> 01:31:19,639
l'm not an SS man.

1092
01:31:19,745 --> 01:31:24,409
l'm working for British lntelligence.
l'm planning to take over this ship.

1093
01:31:24,484 --> 01:31:25,815
l don't believe you.

1094
01:31:26,586 --> 01:31:28,076
You have no choice.

1095
01:31:28,154 --> 01:31:30,918
You are a Jew on your way to Germany.

1096
01:31:31,057 --> 01:31:34,220
And if you value your life,
you will need my help...

1097
01:31:34,293 --> 01:31:35,624
and l will need yours.

1098
01:31:35,728 --> 01:31:37,457
How can l be of help to you?

1099
01:31:37,563 --> 01:31:40,657
Well, l cannot take over this ship
without the American prisoners...

1100
01:31:40,766 --> 01:31:43,234
and l may need your help to contact them.

1101
01:31:43,302 --> 01:31:45,270
Why don't you contact them yourself?

1102
01:31:45,338 --> 01:31:46,600
l am going to try.

1103
01:31:46,672 --> 01:31:49,573
But the message exposing me
is on its way from Berlin.

1104
01:31:49,642 --> 01:31:52,133
And if it comes by 8:00 tonight,
when the watch changes...

1105
01:31:52,245 --> 01:31:55,146
then you will have to slip into the hold
and persuade them.

1106
01:31:55,248 --> 01:31:57,944
They will not believe
any of the men with me.

1107
01:31:58,150 --> 01:32:02,587
And if our plan succeeds, we'll be finished
with this idiotic war in a few days.

1108
01:32:02,655 --> 01:32:04,520
You think this war is idiotic?

1109
01:32:04,824 --> 01:32:06,416
All wars are idiotic.

1110
01:32:06,492 --> 01:32:08,323
One is not different from the other.

1111
01:32:09,262 --> 01:32:10,695
Then why are you here?

1112
01:32:10,796 --> 01:32:12,286
Certainly not by choice.

1113
01:32:12,598 --> 01:32:16,432
l was blackmailed by a Britisher
to the strains of Mozart.

1114
01:32:17,370 --> 01:32:21,033
l am not concerned about this war.
l don't care who wins or loses.

1115
01:32:21,607 --> 01:32:23,939
But l am concerned about the Gestapo.

1116
01:32:24,677 --> 01:32:28,010
You have no idea
what these people are capable of.

1117
01:32:30,449 --> 01:32:31,473
Like....

1118
01:32:32,885 --> 01:32:36,514
Like maybe force me to have sex
with my brother?

1119
01:32:37,523 --> 01:32:38,990
Or something like that?

1120
01:32:40,526 --> 01:32:45,225
And maybe kill Bernie
if he's not able to have sex with me?

1121
01:32:46,666 --> 01:32:50,397
And, then, maybe make me sleep
with all of them...

1122
01:32:51,637 --> 01:32:55,630
all 17 of them, hour after hour.

1123
01:33:00,913 --> 01:33:02,904
Quiet. Quiet.

1124
01:33:04,417 --> 01:33:05,475
Be still.

1125
01:33:08,154 --> 01:33:11,590
While you were listening to your Mozart...

1126
01:33:12,425 --> 01:33:15,758
my mother and my father were marched...

1127
01:33:16,495 --> 01:33:19,396
to the gas chamber
where they were killed.

1128
01:33:19,865 --> 01:33:22,993
You want to tell me about the Gestapo?

1129
01:33:23,903 --> 01:33:25,871
Get out! Get out!

1130
01:33:25,938 --> 01:33:26,996
Be quiet.

1131
01:33:27,106 --> 01:33:28,903
-Get out!
-Quiet!

1132
01:33:29,308 --> 01:33:31,105
HeIIo, Midshipman EmiI Brinkmann...

1133
01:33:31,243 --> 01:33:35,202
your father, GeneraI Franz Brinkmann,
awarded the Knight's Cross with swords.

1134
01:33:35,281 --> 01:33:37,613
Engineer Mark Leicht,
we hope you are Iistening.

1135
01:33:37,717 --> 01:33:41,244
Your brother, Major Martin Leicht
awarded the Knight's Cross...

1136
01:33:41,354 --> 01:33:44,585
after a daring bombing mission
over Rostov on the Russian front.

1137
01:33:44,690 --> 01:33:47,420
HeIIo, Capt. RoIf MueIIer,
